         b'y-recommender-systems category-sharing category-talk" id="post-7'
         b'9">\n\t\t\t<h2>Poolcasting</h2>\n\n\t\t\t<div class="entry">\n'
         b'\t\t\t\t<p><a href="http://www.iiia.csic.es/~claudio/">Claudio</a> ('
         b'from <a href="http://www.iiia.csic.es/">IIIA</a> and sponsored by <a'
         b' href="http://www.mystrands.com/download">MyStrands</a>) gave a very'
         b' interesting <a href="http://www.iiia.csic.es/seminar_detail.php?sem'
         b'_id=36">talk</a> about  poolcasting (<a href="http://www.iiia.csic.e'
         b's/~claudio/keynotes/Baccigalupo-2007-ICCBR-Presentation.pdf">pdf</a>'
         b' of his slides). Poolcasting is a web radio in which individuals may'
         b' join different channels. Those subscribed to a channel will listen '
         b'to the same stream of songs. The problem is how to select the songs '
         b'on that stream. Claudio <a href="http://www.iiia.csic.es/~claudio/pa'
         b'pers/Baccigalupo-Plaza-2007-ICCBR.pdf">did so </a>by combining the p'
         b'references of a channel\xc2\xb4s listeners using <a href="http://e'
         b'n.wikipedia.org/wiki/Case-based_reasoning">Case-Based Reasoning</a>.'
         b'</p>\n<p>The same approach may be used for <a href="http://mobblo'
         b'g.cs.ucl.ac.uk/2007/08/17/mobile-music/">mobile music</a>. A bar may'
         b' decide to play songs depending on the preferences of its customers '
         b'(and preferences may be elicited from the playlists that  customers '
         b'store on their mp3 players or mobile phones).</p>\n<p>A couple of'
         b' questions that might be of interest to some of us: what if listener'
         b's do not share many songs in their playlists? Would it be possible t'
         b'o factor listeners\xc2\xb4 reputation (trust)  in deciding which s'
         b'ongs to play?</p>\n\n\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\n\t\t\t\t<p class="postmetada'
         b'ta alt">\n\t\t\t\t\t<small>\n\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\tThis entry was'
