         b'8/poolcasting/#comment-1100">\n\t\t\tSeptember 18, 2007 at 5:35 pm</'
         b'a>\t\t</div>\n\n\t\t<p>Well, since listenings are on a power law, '
         b'the most popular bands (Beatles, Red Hot Chilli Peppers and Radiohea'
         b'd, according to last.fm) have the highest chance of being liked by e'
         b'verybody. In other words: when you have a heterogeneous audience, go'
         b'ing mainstream is probably the best you can do (that&#8217;s why the'
         b' market does it when the offer is limited, after all!).</p>\n<p>I'
         b' wonder what would happen if this mechanism would be used: would peo'
         b'ple choose places where they like the music, creating a feedback eff'
         b'ect that encourages specialization, or would all places converge to '
         b'the same kind of mainstream music?</p>\n\n\t\t<div class="reply"'
